 This plan addresses the need for a production-grade, advanced sandbox environment for cybersecurity operations. Based on the    
     provided documentation (advanced_sandbox_cybersecurity.md, advanced_sandbox_framework.md, and the comprehensive Word document   
     analysis), the project aims to build a multi-layered sandbox platform that combines:

     - Malware analysis capabilities with evasion resistance
     - AI/LLM agent sandboxing for safe autonomous code execution
     - Real-time behavioral monitoring via eBPF
     - Threat intelligence integration for closed-loop security operations
     - Remote browser isolation for zero-trust web interactions
     - Document sanitization for safe file handling

     The goal is to create a unified, scalable platform that serves both defensive security operations (malware triage, threat       
     hunting) and secure development needs (AI code execution, untrusted code analysis).

     ---
     Recommended Architecture: Modular Multi-Layer Sandbox Platform

     Core Design Principle

     Build a modular orchestration layer that integrates best-in-class open-source components rather than reinventing foundational   
     technologies. This approach maximizes security maturity while minimizing development risk.

     ---
     Phase 1: Foundation Layer (Months 1-3)

     Objective: Deploy core malware analysis sandbox with threat intelligence integration

     Components:

     1. CAPEv2 as the primary malware detonation sandbox
       - File: vendor/CAPEv2/ (submodule from https://github.com/kevoreilly/CAPEv2)
       - Configuration: Windows 10 VM with deception artifacts, YARA signature database
       - Integration points: MISP for TI correlation, Sigma rules for behavioral detection
     2. MISP (Malware Information Sharing Platform) for threat intelligence
       - File: vendor/MISP/ (submodule from https://github.com/MISP/MISP)
       - Pre-load with: VirusTotal Intelligence feeds, MalwareBazaar IOCs, EMBER dataset
     3. Sigma HQ rule engine for behavioral detection
       - File: vendor/sigma/ (submodule from https://github.com/SigmaHQ/sigma)
       - Deploy as post-analysis correlation engine on CAPEv2 output
     4. PostgreSQL for structured IOC storage
       - Schema design: src/database/schema.sql with tables for samples, behaviors, IOCs, verdicts

     Deliverables:
     - Working CAPEv2 deployment with Windows 10 analysis VM
     - Automated sample submission API (src/api/submission.py)
     - MISP integration with automated IOC push/pull
     - Sigma rule matching on behavioral logs
     - Basic analyst dashboard (src/frontend/dashboard.py)

     Verification:
     - Submit 10 known malware samples from MalwareBazaar
     - Verify IOC extraction and MISP enrichment
     - Confirm Sigma rules flag expected behaviors
     - Measure analysis completion time (<10 min per sample)

     ---
     Phase 2: Behavioral Monitoring Layer (Months 4-6)

     Objective: Implement real-time system call interception and behavioral analysis

     Components:

     1. Azazel eBPF runtime tracer for containerized analysis
       - File: vendor/azazel/ (submodule from https://github.com/beelzebub-labs/azazel)
       - Deploy alongside CAPEv2 for kernel-level telemetry
       - Output: NDJSON stream to Elasticsearch/Splunk
     2. Falco for cloud-native runtime security
       - File: vendor/falco/ (submodule from https://github.com/falcosecurity/falco)
       - Monitor sandbox infrastructure for escape attempts
       - Rules: Custom ruleset for sandbox-specific anomalies
     3. Custom ML classifier for false positive reduction
       - File: src/ml/false_positive_classifier.py
       - Features: API call n-grams, process tree embeddings, network beaconing scores
       - Model: XGBoost + SHAP for explainability
       - Training data: EMBER dataset + CAPEv2 historical logs

     Deliverables:
     - eBPF telemetry pipeline capturing syscall-level events
     - Falco alerting on sandbox escape indicators
     - ML classifier reducing false positives by >30%
     - Analyst feedback loop for model retraining

     Verification:
     - Run benign software suite, verify low false positive rate (<5%)
     - Run known malware, confirm eBPF captures syscall sequences
     - Test ML classifier on 1000-sample holdout set, measure precision/recall
     - Simulate sandbox escape attempt, verify Falco detection

     ---
     Phase 3: AI Agent Sandboxing (Months 7-9)

     Objective: Secure execution environment for autonomous AI agents and LLM-generated code

     Components:

     1. E2B or Modal for ephemeral code execution
       - File: vendor/e2b/ (submodule from https://github.com/e2b-dev/E2B)
       - Use case: AI code interpreter, untrusted function execution
       - Configuration: Sub-second cold start, strict egress policies
     2. gVisor for container kernel isolation
       - File: vendor/gvisor/ (submodule from https://github.com/google/gvisor)
       - Deploy as runtime for E2B sandboxes
       - Intercept syscalls at user-space boundary
     3. Agent orchestration framework (Cline or Aider)
       - File: src/ai/orchestrator.py
       - Features: Tool denylist, command validation, output sanitization
       - Integration: E2B SDK for run_code() calls
     4. Network egress throttling via Tailscale or ZeroTier
       - File: src/network/egress_policy.py
       - Block: Known C2 patterns, data exfiltration indicators
       - Allow: Whitelisted APIs only (GitHub, PyPI, etc.)

     Deliverables:
     - Secure code interpreter API (src/api/code_interpreter.py)
     - AI agent tool framework with sandboxed execution
     - Network micro-segmentation preventing lateral movement
     - Audit logging for all AI-generated actions

     Verification:
     - Submit AI-generated code with known destructive patterns (rm -rf, DROP TABLE), verify block
     - Test cold start time (<2 seconds for micro-VM)
     - Attempt network exfiltration, confirm egress policy blocks
     - Run 100 benign code submissions, measure success rate

